msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:9
msgid ""
"In this video (09:47), we will provide an overview of the importance of "
"documentation as it relates to data management and data publishing. You will "
"learn about data mapping, data relationships and metadata."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:11
msgid ""
"If you are unable to watch the embedded video, you can xref:"
"attachment$foundations-documentation_v4-720p.mp4[download,opts=download] it "
"locally. (MP4 - 35.2 MB)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide1.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 1 - Foundations - Documentation*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:33
msgid ""
"In this presentation, we will provide an overview of the importance of "
"documentation as it relates to data management and data publishing. You will "
"learn about data mapping, data relationships and metadata."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide2.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 2 - Documentation*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:49
msgid ""
"In the previous Foundations presentations, we looked at the individual "
"elements that make up both your data and the containers that hold it. Now "
"we’ll look at ways to document those data and what you want to do with it.  "
"  According to the director Steven Spielberg,   “People have forgotten how "
"to tell a story. Stories don’t have a middle or an end any more. They "
"usually have a beginning that never stops beginning.” (Steven Spielberg)    "
"Documentation is the story of your project or dataset. There should always "
"be a concrete beginning, middle and end.    In essence you should be able to "
"answer certain questions at specific points:   At the beginning : What did "
"our project aim to do? What was the purpose of creating the dataset?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:51
msgid "In the middle: What did we actually do? What did we achieve?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:53
msgid "At the end: What didn’t we achieve? Why? What should happen next?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:54
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide3.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 3 - Key concepts*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:59
msgid ""
"In order to document your data and render them as fit for use as possible "
"for yourself and future users, you need to follow these three essential "
"steps:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:61
msgid "Mapping your data to existing formats and standards if necessary"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:62
msgid "Planning your data moves"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:63
msgid "Create useful metadata describing your data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide4.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 4 - Mapping data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:78
msgid ""
"We will begin by looking at ways to describe your data, then we will show "
"how to map your data from one data structure to another and finally talk "
"about how to record metadata about your data.    First is mapping data.    "
"This is the process that you will use to describe how the attributes in your "
"dataset can be transformed into attributes in a different one.    Mapping "
"data is the “Process of Identifying the start field(s) within dataset A, and "
"its (their) corresponding field(s) in dataset B.”   In this example Dataset "
"A has 10 columns. There are:  "
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:79
msgid "some integer fields represented by the purple squares,"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:80
msgid "some boolean fields represented by the red triangles"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:81
msgid "some date fields represented by blue pentagons"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:82
msgid "some text fields, green 8 pointed stars"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:83
msgid "and some complex fields"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - Mapping data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:91
msgid ""
"Dataset B has a different set of fields, 15 in total.    What we need to do "
"is identify which fields in Dataset A match which fields in Dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Mapping A to B*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:97
msgid "We do that by describing the relationships."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:106
msgid ""
"For example Dataset A has an ID field and so does Dataset B. We can draw a "
"line directly between the two. This is called a one to one match.    "
"Question: Can you see any other one to one matches? Answer: State, Exp?, "
"Pink Elephant!   Another type of relationship is is a one to many. In these "
"cases there is a single field in dataset A that maps to 2 or more fields in "
"Dataset B. Date is an example.    You many also find cases where a more than "
"one field in Dataset A contains data for more than one field in Dataset B. "
"Notes fields are often guilty of this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Planning data moves - Data relationships*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:112
msgid "In fact there are six relationships:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:114
msgid ""
"Some fields will map one-to-one (1:1), meaning that the original column in "
"dataset A exactly matches another one in dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:115
msgid ""
"Some fields will map many-to-one (∞:1) , meaning that some columns in "
"dataset A can be merged (or concatenated) to match a single one in dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:116
msgid ""
"Some fields will map one-to-many (1:∞), meaning that one column in dataset A "
"will have to be split into two or more fields in order to match the fields "
"in dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:117
msgid ""
"Some fields might not exist yet zero-to-one (0:1), meaning that some "
"information are not present in dataset A and need to be added in a new "
"column to match an existing field in dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:118
msgid ""
"Some fields might not have a place to go one-to-zero (1:0), meaning that "
"some information present in dataset A does not match any existing field on "
"dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:119
msgid ""
"Some fields will map many-to-many (∞ : ∞), meaning that information in "
"dataset A is scattered in different fields, which do not match exactly "
"existing ones in dataset B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Planning data moves - Transformations*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:125
msgid ""
"Each of the relationship types has its own nuances as to how you are going "
"to have to handle them."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:127
msgid ""
"one-to-one (1:1) - Beware your field types. If they are the not the same. "
"You will need to do some manipulation."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:128
msgid ""
"many-to-one (∞:1) - These fields will need to joined together to go into the "
"field."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:129
msgid ""
"one-to-many (1:∞) - These fields will need to be split apart and put in to "
"different fields"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:130
msgid ""
"zero-to-one (0:1) - Work out how (or if) you can even fill these in. Is the "
"data mixed into a notes field? If so how do you get it out?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:131
msgid ""
"one-to-zero (1:0) - Either throw away the data or add a field.You might not "
"even have a home in the other dataset. Do/Can you create a new field?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:132
msgid ""
"many-to-many (∞ : ∞) - “for the love of a higher being!” This usually means "
"that your incoming data is very messy and will take time to clean before you "
"can map it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:133
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Planning data moves - Mapping document*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:138
msgid ""
"This is an example of what a mapping document looks like. Notice that not "
"only do we document the relationships we also articulate (to the best of our "
"knowledge) what should be done to the data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Metadata*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:146
msgid ""
"We’ve talked a lot about documenting the structures that hold your data but "
"you must also document the information that gives context. This is called "
"metadata and is data about your data!   As we mention in the section on data "
"quality your ”Metadata must be rich enough to allow data (re)use by a third "
"party without them having to refer to the data source.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:147
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:150
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Metadata*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:152
msgid ""
"We will discuss this in more detail in later sessions but as a quick guide "
"good documentation should include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:154
msgid ""
"A title – Which should be descriptive, memorable and if possible unique. "
"Dates are good to include in a dataset name for example to allow you to "
"track versions."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:155
msgid ""
"A narrative – Should describe the rationale for the creation of the dataset. "
"It should include at least general information about spatial, temporal and "
"taxonomic coverage and give the potential user a broad picture of uses that "
"may be appropriate for the data without further transformation."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:156
msgid ""
"Source information – If you did not collect or measure the data yourself, "
"where or who did you get if from?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:157
msgid ""
"Lineage – Does the dataset have a history? Have any of the fields been "
"transformed in any way from the original?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:158
msgid ""
"Statement of accuracy – Using the concepts of accuracy, precision, errors "
"and uncertainty that we discussed previously, are there any issues with the "
"dataset that should be known to a user?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:159
msgid ""
"Dates and life expectancy – When will the dataset be available? How long is "
"it valid for? When if ever will it be updated?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:160
msgid ""
"Field Definitions – Describing the format of fields and what kind of data "
"each contains. Was any cleaning or transformation down to the original data? "
"This is important for you to know if you are mapping it to a standard such "
"as Darwin Core."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:161
msgid ""
"Collection methodology – How was the data collected? Where there protocols "
"used which will affect its fitness for use?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:162
msgid "Statement of completeness – What is missing from the data and why?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:163
msgid ""
"Conditions of use and constraints – Where and how can you use the data? For "
"most portals and GBIF in particular data must use very open licensing, so "
"understanding the requirements of data owners and their institutions is very "
"important."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:164
msgid ""
"Custodianship/Contact information – This should be the institution "
"responsible for the dataset as presented to you, as well as (if possible) "
"the individual who created the dataset. There should also be a technical "
"contact who is responsible for the publication of the dataset."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-documentation.adoc:165
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-documentation-Slide12.png"
msgstr ""

